{"title_page": "Canadian (canoe)", "text_new": "[[File:1998-10-tema-canoe.jpg|thumb|Touring canoe]]\n[[File:Vajda Attila.jpg|thumb|x160px|Racing canoe]]\n'''Canadian''' is the byname used in some countries for the descendants of the birch bark [[canoe]] used by the [[North American Indians]] as a means of transportation in the densely forested and impassable areas of [[North America]].\n\nIn the [[United Kingdom]] and some other European countries the [[kayak]] is considered to be a kind of canoe. Technically this is understandable, as one can easily see when a whitewater kayak is converted into a decked whitewater canoe just by taking the seat out and paddle it kneeling with a single blade paddle. To distinguish an open or decked canoe from a kayak, a [[Canoe#Touring and camping|touring]], [[Whitewater canoeing|whitewater]] and racing [[canoe]] are then often called 'Canadian canoe', or 'Canadian' for short<ref>https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/1911_Encyclop%C3%A6dia_Britannica/Canoe</ref>: e.g. [[:de:Kanadier|Kanadier]] in German, [[:sv:Kanadensare|Kanadensare]] in Swedish and [[:nl:Canadese kano|Canadees]] in Dutch.\n\nAll in all this practice has become problematic for all the confusion it leads to: like kayaks that are called canoes and canoes sometimes even called 'canadian' kayaks!\n\n== History ==\n[[File:PrinceOfWalesCanoeing.jpg|upright=1|thumb|\"Canadian Style\" canoe]]\n[[File:Seliga.jpg|thumb|upright=1|Wood & Canvas canoe]]\n[[File:Dickerson-C1a.jpg|thumb|upright=1|Decked whitewater canoe]]\nThe use of this byname 'Canadian' is the result of misinterpretations during the development of the sport of canoeing in the 19th Century, where the kayak was seen as the canoe, and an open [[Canoe#Touring and camping| touring canoe ]] was then called 'Canadian canoe' from the so-called \"Canadian style\" canoe from Canada, the then more or less 'approved' open canoe model by the [[American Canoe Association]] (ACA), as opposed to the Wood & Canvas canoe from Maine in the United States that was not officially recognized by the ACA until 1934.<ref>Jeffrey Charles Swenson, [https://books.google.nl/books?id=fwa_NwAACAAJ Canoe Passages: Cross-cultural Conveyance in U.S. and Canadian Literature, page 167]</ref><ref>Roy MacGregor, [http://books.google.nl/books?id=81KWBgAAQBAJ Canoe Country: The Making of Canada, page 216]</ref>\n\nFor the canoeing clubs and associations of the 19th Century a canoe was a decked, double-ended boat, propelled with a double-blade paddle or sailed. The open canoes of that time were often identified as '[[Peterborough, Ontario|Peterborough]]' or 'Rice Lake' canoes, from the locations where early cedar-strip boats were first made, thus 'Canadian' canoes. The canoe associations at that time, however, for large part consisted of somewhat elitist [rich] people with the opinion that a [[Canoe#Touring and camping| touring canoe ]] was only really good if one could sail well with it. Therefore, only the 'Canadian style' canoe was approved by them. Canoes like the birch bark canoe and its direct descendant the Wood & Canvas canoe were considered inferior: \"a rag canoe, only suitable for workmen and primitive natives\" [sic].\n\nIn America, the canoe lost its qualifying prefix 'Canadian' not long afterwards and canoes were simply called 'canoes' (open or decked). In several European countries though, people were not aware of these discrepancies, and because they saw kayaks as canoes they kept calling all kind of canoes 'Canadian canoes' \u2013 even the decked whitewater canoes\u2026 This has caused much confusion about canoes and kayaks in these countries, also because the byname 'Canadian' is not used consistently.<br />\nThe fact that a kayak was seen as a canoe in some countries was also one of the reasons for [[Sprint canoe#Women's canoe| women not to be allowed to canoe]] at the [[Olympic games]] until 2020<ref>http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/women-canoe-2020-olympics-tokyo-1.4175083</ref>, because one of the arguments was that women were already allowed to canoe because a kayak is a canoe\u2026\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Sprint canoe]]\n* [[Canoe slalom]]\n* [[Wildwater canoeing]]\n* [[Kayak]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.canoeicf.com/history Canoe and Kayak History \u2013 ICF History of Canoeing] at [[International Canoe Federation]]\n* [https://nmmc.co.uk/object/boats/peterborough-canoe/ Peterborough canoe at National Maritime Museum Cornwall]\n* [http://www.virtualmuseum.ca/edu/ViewLoitDa.do?method=preview&lang=EN&id=11937 Payne Dugout Canoe at the Virtual Museum of Canada]\n\n[[Category:Canoes]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:1998-10-tema-canoe.jpg|thumb|Touring canoe]]\n[[File:Vajda Attila.jpg|thumb|x160px|Racing canoe]]\n'''Canadian''' is the byname used in some countries for the descendants of the birch bark canoe used by the [[North American Indians]] as a means of transportation in the densely forested and impassable areas of [[North America]].\n\nIn the [[United Kingdom]] and some other European countries the [[kayak]] is considered to be a kind of canoe. Technically this is understandable, as one can easily see when a whitewater kayak is converted into a decked whitewater canoe just by taking the seat out and paddle it kneeling with a single blade paddle. To distinguish an open or decked canoe from a kayak, a [[Canoe#Touring and camping|touring]], [[Whitewater canoeing|whitewater]] and racing [[canoe]] are then often called 'Canadian canoe', or 'Canadian' for short<ref>https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/1911_Encyclop%C3%A6dia_Britannica/Canoe</ref>: e.g. [[:de:Kanadier|Kanadier]] in German, [[:sv:Kanadensare|Kanadensare]] in Swedish and [[:nl:Canadese kano|Canadees]] in Dutch.\n\nAll in all this practice has become problematic for all the confusion it leads to: like kayaks that are called canoes and canoes sometimes even called 'canadian' kayaks!\n\n== History ==\n[[File:PrinceOfWalesCanoeing.jpg|upright=1|thumb|\"Canadian Style\" canoe]]\n[[File:Seliga.jpg|thumb|upright=1|Wood & Canvas canoe]]\n[[File:Dickerson-C1a.jpg|thumb|upright=1|Decked whitewater canoe]]\nThe use of this byname 'Canadian' is the result of misinterpretations during the development of the sport of canoeing in the 19th Century, where the kayak was seen as the canoe, and an open [[Canoe#Touring and camping| touring canoe ]] was then called 'Canadian canoe' from the so-called \"Canadian style\" canoe from Canada, the then more or less 'approved' open canoe model by the [[American Canoe Association]] (ACA), as opposed to the Wood & Canvas canoe from Maine in the United States that was not officially recognized by the ACA until 1934.<ref>Jeffrey Charles Swenson, [https://books.google.nl/books?id=fwa_NwAACAAJ Canoe Passages: Cross-cultural Conveyance in U.S. and Canadian Literature, page 167]</ref><ref>Roy MacGregor, [http://books.google.nl/books?id=81KWBgAAQBAJ Canoe Country: The Making of Canada, page 216]</ref>\n\nFor the canoeing clubs and associations of the 19th Century a canoe was a decked, double-ended boat, propelled with a double-blade paddle or sailed. The open canoes of that time were often identified as '[[Peterborough, Ontario|Peterborough]]' or 'Rice Lake' canoes, from the locations where early cedar-strip boats were first made, thus 'Canadian' canoes. The canoe associations at that time, however, for large part consisted of somewhat elitist [rich] people with the opinion that a [[Canoe#Touring and camping| touring canoe ]] was only really good if one could sail well with it. Therefore, only the 'Canadian style' canoe was approved by them. Canoes like the birch bark canoe and its direct descendant the Wood & Canvas canoe were considered inferior: \"a rag canoe, only suitable for workmen and primitive natives\" [sic].\n\nIn America, the canoe lost its qualifying prefix 'Canadian' not long afterwards and canoes were simply called 'canoes' (open or decked). In several European countries though, people were not aware of these discrepancies, and because they saw kayaks as canoes they kept calling all kind of canoes 'Canadian canoes' \u2013 even the decked whitewater canoes\u2026 This has caused much confusion about canoes and kayaks in these countries, also because the byname 'Canadian' is not used consistently.<br />\nThe fact that a kayak was seen as a canoe in some countries was also one of the reasons for [[Sprint canoe#Women's canoe| women not to be allowed to canoe]] at the [[Olympic games]] until 2020<ref>http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/women-canoe-2020-olympics-tokyo-1.4175083</ref>, because one of the arguments was that women were already allowed to canoe because a kayak is a canoe\u2026\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Sprint canoe]]\n* [[Canoe slalom]]\n* [[Wildwater canoeing]]\n* [[Kayak]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.canoeicf.com/history Canoe and Kayak History \u2013 ICF History of Canoeing] at [[International Canoe Federation]]\n* [https://nmmc.co.uk/object/boats/peterborough-canoe/ Peterborough canoe at National Maritime Museum Cornwall]\n* [http://www.virtualmuseum.ca/edu/ViewLoitDa.do?method=preview&lang=EN&id=11937 Payne Dugout Canoe at the Virtual Museum of Canada]\n\n[[Category:Canoes]]\n", "name_user": "Kanoniem", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canadian_(canoe)"}
{"title_page": "Guinguette", "text_new": "[[File:Auguste Renoir - Luncheon of the Boating Party 1880-1881.jpg|right|thumb|230px|Guinguette atmosphere in the ''[[Luncheon of the Boating Party|D\u00e9jeuner de Canotiers]]'' of [[Auguste Renoir]]]]\n[[File:Vincent Willem van Gogh 043.jpg|thumb|230px|''La guinguette'', [[Vincent van Gogh]].]] \n'''Guinguettes''' were popular drinking establishments located in the suburbs of [[Paris]] and other cities in [[France]]. Guinguettes would also serve as restaurants and, often, as dance venues. The origin of the term comes from ''guinguet'', indicating a sour white light local wine. \n\nThe 1750 ''Dictionnaire de la langue fran\u00e7aise'', defined Guinguette as a \"Small cabaret in the suburbs and the surrounds of Paris, where craftsmen drink in the summer and on Sundays and on Festival days. This term is new. It comes apparently from what are sold in these cabarets: a sour light local green wine, that is called ''ginguet'', such as found around Paris.\" A ''[[Goguette]]'' was a similar kind of establishment.\n\n==History==\nDuring the 18th century, a [[consumer revolution]] led once isolated villages and hamlets outside Paris to be swept up in a booming material culture. Commodities, and particularly alcohol, consumed outside the customs barrier of the city were considerably cheaper, being exempt from state taxes. This encouraged the growth of an entertainment industry just beyond the taxman's reach and a network of drinking establishments was established. They were especially popular on Sundays and holidays, when Parisians would visit to enjoy themselves and to get drunk cheaply.<ref>Colin Jones ''Paris - Biography of a City'', p226, Allen Lane 2004, {{ISBN|0-7139-9321-9}}</ref> Today, the term 'guinguette' is still used for a waterside refreshment stand, particularly open-air, all over France.<ref name=Deberne>Henri Joannis Deberne, ''Danser en soci\u00e9t\u00e9'', Christine Bonneton editor, 3/1999, Paris {{ISBN|2-86253-229-0}}</ref>\n\nThe development of railways in the 1880s and the establishment of the \"[[Gare de la Bastille]]\" (''[[Bastille]] station'') with many trains serving the eastern suburbs of Paris (such as [[Nogent sur Marne]]) contributed to the success of guinguettes.<ref name=Deberne/>\n\n==Geography==\nThe majority are on the edges of the [[Seine]] and the [[Marne (river)|Marne]], and some are in a district that stretches to the outskirts of [[Rouen]].  Some guinguettes were however far from the rivers, as the picturesque guinguettes of [[le Plessis-Robinson]] built among the chestnut trees. There were hundreds of guinguettes as far away as [[Nogent-sur-Seine]], where the nature of the Seine valley changes most.\n\n==Tradition decline and return==\nToday guinguettes are an object of nostalgia. The guinguettes were marvellous places to return to lighter times during the mad years of the [[Roaring Twenties|1920s]]. They were obviously an eminent subject for painting during the first half of the 20th century.\n\nBut television and the ban on bathing in the rivers in the 1960s caused the decline of guinguettes. This ban was justified for reasons of hygiene (water quality deteriorated in the 1960s and 1970s) and safety (the risk due to barge traffic and drowning). In the 1960s, guinguettes became a subject of [[nostalgia]]. Many people forgot guinguettes, as the French scriptwriter ''Michel Audiard'' had one of his characters point out. Since the 1980s, there has been a small revival, particularly along the Marne river. Even now in 2008, some guinguettes stay open every weekend.\n\nAs of 2011 a gradual return to modern guinguettes has started.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/2011/jun/28/world/la-fg-france-guinguettes-20110629 Los Angeles Times June 28, 2011, by Devorah Lauter]</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|France}}\n*[[Bal-musette]]\n*[[Goguette]]\n*[[Eug\u00e8ne Imbert]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Movies with guinguettes ==\n* ''Nogent, Eldorado du dimanche'' (=\"Nogent, sunday eldorado\") - [[Marcel Carn\u00e9]], 1929\n* ''[[La belle \u00e9quipe]]'' (=\"the fine crew\") - [[Julien Duvivier]], 1936 with [[Jean Gabin]] singing the well-known waltz ''Quand on s'prom\u00e8ne au bord de l'eau'' (=\"walking on the river bank\")\n* ''[[Casque d'or]]'' (=\"golden helmet\") - [[Jacques Becker]], 1952\n\n== External links ==\n* {{in lang|fr}} [http://www.guinguette.fr web site of a guinguette on Marne river]\n* {{in lang|fr}} [http://www.culture-guinguette.com/ website of the association \"culture guinguette\"]\n\n[[Category:French culture]]\n[[Category:Dance venues]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Auguste Renoir - Luncheon of the Boating Party 1880-1881.jpg|right|thumb|230px|Guinguette atmosphere in the ''[[Luncheon of the Boating Party|D\u00e9jeuner de Canotiers]]'' of [[Auguste Renoir]]]]\n[[File:Vincent Willem van Gogh 043.jpg|thumb|230px|''La guinguette'', [[Vincent van Gogh]].]] \n'''Guinguettes''' were popular drinking establishments located in the suburbs of [[Paris]] and other cities in [[France]]. Guinguettes would also serve as restaurants and, often, as dance venues. The origin of the term comes from ''guinguet'', indicating a sour white light local wine. \n\nThe 1750 ''Dictionnaire de la langue fran\u00e7aise'', defined Guinguette as a \"Small cabaret in the suburbs and the surrounds of Paris, where craftsmen drink in the summer and on Sundays and on Festival days. This term is new. It comes apparently from what are sold in these cabarets: a sour light local green wine, that is called ''ginguet'', such as found around Paris.\" A ''[[Goguette]]'' was a similar kind of establishment.\n\n==History==\nDuring the 18th century, a [[consumer revolution]] led once isolated villages and hamlets outside Paris to be swept up in a booming material culture. Commodities, and particularly alcohol, consumed outside the customs barrier of the city were considerably cheaper, being exempt from state taxes. This encouraged the growth of an entertainment industry just beyond the taxman's reach and a network of drinking establishments was established. They were especially popular on Sundays and holidays, when Parisians would visit to enjoy themselves and to get drunk cheaply.<ref>Colin Jones ''Paris - Biography of a City'', p226, Allen Lane 2004, {{ISBN|0-7139-9321-9}}</ref> Today, the term 'guinguette' is still used for a waterside refreshment stand, particularly open-air, all over France.<ref name=Deberne>Henri Joannis Deberne, ''Danser en soci\u00e9t\u00e9'', Christine Bonneton editor, 3/1999, Paris {{ISBN|2-86253-229-0}}</ref>\n\nThe development of railways in the 1880s and the establishment of the \"[[Gare de la Bastille]]\" (''[[Bastille]] station'') with many trains serving the eastern suburbs of Paris (such as [[Nogent sur Marne]]) contributed to the success of guinguettes.<ref name=Deberne/>\n\n==Geography==\nThe majority are on the edges of the [[Seine]] and the [[Marne (river)|Marne]], and some are in a district that stretches to the outskirts of [[Rouen]].  Some guinguettes were however far from the rivers, as the picturesque guinguettes of [[le Plessis-Robinson]] built among the chestnut trees. There were hundreds of guinguettes as far away as [[Nogent-sur-Seine]], where the nature of the Seine valley changes most.\n\n==Tradition decline and return==\nToday guinguettes are an object of nostalgia. The guinguettes were marvellous places to return to lighter times during the mad years of the [[Roaring Twenties|1920s]]. They were obviously an eminent subject for painting during the first half of the 20th century.\n\nBut television and the ban on bathing in the rivers in the 1960s caused the decline of guinguettes. This ban was justified for reasons of hygiene (water quality deteriorated in the 1960s and 1970s) and safety (the risk due to barge traffic and drowning). In the 1960s, guinguettes became a subject of [[nostalgia]]. Many people forgot guinguettes, as the French scriptwriter ''Michel Audiard'' had one of his characters point out. Since the 1980s, there has been a small revival, particularly along the Marne river. Even now in 2008, some guinguettes stay open every weekend.\n\nAs of 2011 a gradual return to modern guinguettes had started.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/2011/jun/28/world/la-fg-france-guinguettes-20110629 Los Angeles Times June 28, 2011, by Devorah Lauter]</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|France}}\n*[[Bal-musette]]\n*[[Goguette]]\n*[[Eug\u00e8ne Imbert]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Movies with guinguettes ==\n* ''Nogent, Eldorado du dimanche'' (=\"Nogent, sunday eldorado\") - [[Marcel Carn\u00e9]], 1929\n* ''[[La belle \u00e9quipe]]'' (=\"the fine crew\") - [[Julien Duvivier]], 1936 with [[Jean Gabin]] singing the well-known waltz ''Quand on s'prom\u00e8ne au bord de l'eau'' (=\"walking on the river bank\")\n* ''[[Casque d'or]]'' (=\"golden helmet\") - [[Jacques Becker]], 1952\n\n== External links ==\n* {{in lang|fr}} [http://www.guinguette.fr web site of a guinguette on Marne river]\n* {{in lang|fr}} [http://www.culture-guinguette.com/ website of the association \"culture guinguette\"]\n\n[[Category:French culture]]\n[[Category:Dance venues]]\n", "name_user": "Hanengerda", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTradition decline and return", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guinguette"}
